# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: che-cyrillic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:che-cyrillic/4] Brahmi numerals represented 1, 2, and 3 with as many lines.
[src:che-cyrillic/4] 4 was simplified by joining its four lines into a cross that looks like the modern plus sign.
[src:che-cyrillic/4] The Shunga would add a horizontal line on top of the digit, and the Kshatrapa and Pallava evolved the digit to a point where the speed of writing was a secondary concern.
[src:che-cyrillic/4] The Arabs' 4 still had the early concept of the cross, but for the sake of efficiency, was made in one stroke by connecting the "western" end to the "northern" end; the "eastern" end was finished off with a curve.
[src:che-cyrillic/4] The Europeans dropped the finishing curve and gradually made the digit less cursive, ending up with a digit very close to the original Brahmin cross.
[src:che-cyrillic/4] While the shape of the character for the digit 4 has an ascender in most modern typefaces, in typefaces with text figures the glyph usually has a descender, as, for example, in .
[src:che-cyrillic/4] On the seven-segment displays of pocket calculators and digital watches, as well as certain optical character recognition fonts, 4 is seen with an open top: .
[src:che-cyrillic/4] Television stations that operate on channel 4 have occasionally made use of another variation of the "open 4", with the open portion being on the side, rather than the top.
[src:che-cyrillic/4] This version resembles the Canadian Aboriginal syllabics letter ᔦ.
[src:che-cyrillic/4] The magnetic ink character recognition "CMC-7" font also uses this variety of "4".
[src:che-cyrillic/4] Lagrange's four-square theorem states that every positive integer can be written as the sum of at most four squares.
[src:che-cyrillic/4] Four is one of four all-Harshad numbers.
[src:che-cyrillic/4] Each natural number divisible by 4 is a difference of squares of two natural numbers, i.e. $4x=y^{2}-z^{2}$ .
[src:che-cyrillic/4] A four-sided plane figure is a quadrilateral or quadrangle, sometimes also called a *tetragon*.
[src:che-cyrillic/4] It can be further classified as a rectangle or *oblong*, kite, rhombus, and square.
[src:che-cyrillic/4] Four is the highest degree general polynomial equation for which there is a solution in radicals.
[src:che-cyrillic/4] Four is the only square number $N=n\times n$ where $N-1$ is a prime number.
[src:che-cyrillic/4] The four-color theorem states that a planar graph (or, equivalently, a flat map of two-dimensional regions such as countries) can be colored using four colors, so that adjacent vertices (or regions) are always different colors.
[src:che-cyrillic/4] Three colors are not, in general, sufficient to guarantee this.
[src:che-cyrillic/4] The largest planar complete graph has four vertices.
[src:che-cyrillic/4] A solid figure with four faces as well as four vertices is a tetrahedron, which is the smallest possible number of faces and vertices a polyhedron can have.
[src:che-cyrillic/4] The regular tetrahedron, also called a 3-simplex, is the simplest Platonic solid.
[src:che-cyrillic/4] It has four regular triangles as faces that are themselves at dual positions with the vertices of another tetrahedron.
[src:che-cyrillic/4] The smallest non-cyclic group has four elements; it is the Klein four-group.
[src:che-cyrillic/4] *An* alternating groups are not simple for values n ≤ 4 .
[src:che-cyrillic/4] They are defined as locally trivial fibrations that map $f:S^{2n-1}\rightarrow S^{n}$ for values of $n=2,4,8$ (aside from the trivial fibration mapping between two points and a circle).
[src:che-cyrillic/4] In Knuth's up-arrow notation, $2+2=2\times 2=2^{2}=2\uparrow \uparrow 2=2\uparrow \uparrow \uparrow 2=\;...\;=4$ , and so forth, for any number of up arrows.
[src:che-cyrillic/4] There are four dimensions in the theory of Minkowski space, three of space and the one being time.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] The Cyrillic letter А was derived directly from the Greek letter Alpha (Α α).
[src:che-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In the Early Cyrillic alphabet its name was азъ (azǔ), meaning the personal pronoun "I".
[src:che-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In the Cyrillic numeral system, the Cyrillic letter А has a value of 1.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] Throughout history, the Cyrillic letter А has had various shapes, but today is standardized on one that looks exactly like the Latin letter A, including the italic and lower case forms.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In most languages that use the Cyrillic alphabet – such as Bulgarian, Ukrainian, Belarusian, Russian, Rusyn, Serbian, Macedonian and Montenegrin – the Cyrillic letter А represents the open central unrounded vowel /a/.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In Ingush and Chechen, the Cyrillic letter А represents both the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/ when stressed and the mid-central vowel /ə/ when unstressed.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In Turkic languages that use the Cyrillic script it represents the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/, with the exception of Volga Tatar, in which it represents the open back rounded vowel /ɒ/, and Uzbek, in which it represents the near-open front unrounded vowel /æ/.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In languages that contrast vowel length the letter can be written as double vowel.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is used in the Chuvash and in both Eastern Khanty and Northern Khanty alphabets.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It appears in some Nenets dictionaries as well.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In certain orthographical varieties of Bulgarian, such as in the Primer with Various Instructions, this letter was used for the sound /ɤ/.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In modern Bulgarian, this sound is represented by the letter Ъ.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In Chuvash, ⟨ӑ⟩ represents the mid central vowel [ə], as ⟨a⟩ in word "er**a**".
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is always reduced and can occur stressed only in the first syllable of a polysyllabic word.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] The sound varies in its phonetic realization from a reduced /i/ or [ə] (like the pronunciation of ⟨a⟩ in English "sof**a**") to a labialized version of the ⟨a⟩ in English "**a**ll" (with rounded lips).
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is sometimes so reduced as to sound coalesced with the following consonant as in сӑтел *table*, /stel/.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Nineteenth century polymath Mykhailo Maksymovych used an orthography for the Ukrainian language based on etymological principles of spelling, which included the letter А̂ .
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] This letter is also used in some dialects of South Slavic languages such as Bulgarian and Serbian (e.g. гла̂ва or кра̂к).
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̂ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̂ (U+0302).
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It is used in the Khanty, Kildin Sami, Ter Sami, and Hill Mari languages.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Also, this letter was once used in the Gagauz language (which was substituted with ⟨аь⟩).
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It was used in the Bashkir language at the end of the 19th century.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It corresponds to the Cyrillic letter schwa ⟨ә⟩ in modern Bashkir.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] This letter also appears in Bulgarian and Serbian in some of its dialects.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Hill Mari and Gagauz this letter represents the near-open front unrounded vowel, /æ/.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Kildin Sami and Ter Sami this letter represents the open back unrounded vowel /a/ following a palatalized (sometimes also called "half-palatalized") velar nasal /nʲ/ or one of the alveolar stops /tʲ/ or /dʲ/.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Khanty this letter represents the near-open central vowel /ɐ/.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Some languages represent as /ja/, like in letter "Я".
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] A with diaeresis is used in some South Slavic languages, mainly in the Bulgarian and Serbian language to be used for easily shifting the accents in the above languages not only in declensions but elsewhere: брӓт or млāдä.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the Aleut (Bering dialect), Evenki, Ingush, Mansi, Nanai, Orok, Ulch, Kildin Sami, Selkup, and Chechen languages.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron also appears in the Bulgarian and Serbian languages in some dialects.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the South Slavic languages mostly in Bulgarian usually used before or after another stressed vowel: **глāвà**, **крāкà**, **овчāрè**, **ковāчè**, **юнāцѝ**, and **граждāнè**.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-macron-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̄ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̄ (U+0304).
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Хрэстоматия вейска чили збюр выписов з рожных польских ауторов".
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Грамматыка е̨зыка польскего. На кляссэ̨ I". Въ друкарни р̌а̨довэй пр̌и коммиссыи р̌а̨довэй осьвецэня публичнэго.
[src:che-cyrillic/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Lithuania - Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth, Third Partition, Russian Revolution, League of Nations, Klaipėda | Britannica".
[src:che-cyrillic/che-cyrillic] It commonly represents the voiceless postalveolar affricate /tʃ/, like the ⟨tch⟩ in "swi**tch**" or ⟨ch⟩ in "**ch**oice".
[src:che-cyrillic/che-cyrillic] In English, it is romanized typically as ⟨ch⟩ but sometimes as ⟨tch⟩, like in French.
[src:che-cyrillic/che-cyrillic] In German, it can be transcribed as ⟨tsch⟩.
[src:che-cyrillic/che-cyrillic] In Slavic languages using the Latin Alphabet, it is transcribed as ⟨č⟩ so "Tchaikovsky" (Чайковский in Russian) may be transcribed as *Chaykovskiy* or *Čajkovskij*.
[src:che-cyrillic/che-cyrillic] The letter Che (Ч ч) resembles an upside-down lowercase Latin h, as well as resembling the digit 4, especially in digital or open-ended form.
[src:che-cyrillic/che-cyrillic] Cursive forms look like lowercase cursive forms of the letter R.
[src:che-cyrillic/che-cyrillic] The name of Che in the Early Cyrillic alphabet was Чрьвь (*črĭvĭ*), meaning "worm".
[src:che-cyrillic/che-cyrillic] In the Cyrillic numeral system, Che originally did not have a value, however, by the 1300s it started to be used with the numeric value 90 as a replacement for Koppa, some varieties that preserved Koppa around this time used Che with the value 60 instead of the usual letter for it, Ksi.
[src:che-cyrillic/che-cyrillic] Nowadays, Koppa is not used anymore in any variety, and Che has fully replaced it as the letter with the numeric value 90.
[src:che-cyrillic/che-cyrillic] Except for Russian, all Cyrillic-alphabet Slavic languages use Che to represent the voiceless postalveolar affricate /tʃ/ (the **ch** sound in English).
[src:che-cyrillic/che-cyrillic] In Russian, Che usually represents the voiceless alveolo-palatal affricate /t͡ɕ/ (like the Mandarin pronunciation of **j** in pinyin).
[src:che-cyrillic/che-cyrillic] The 1955 draft of Hanyu pinyin adopted the Che for the sound [tɕ] (for which later the letter *j* was used), because of similar pronunciation and resemblance to the corresponding Bopomofo letter ㄐ.
[src:che-cyrillic/che-cyrillic] The Latin Zhuang alphabet used a modified Hindu-Arabic numeral 4, strongly resembling Che, from 1957 to 1986 to represent the fourth (falling) tone.
[src:che-cyrillic/che-cyrillic] In 1986, it was replaced by the Latin letter X.
